Pattern evaluation written to `LCP-UML-7/pattern_evaluation.log`.

Key points:
- Patterns identified: EF Core Unit of Work/Repository (DbContext), DTOs for API inputs, inheritance with TPH discriminators; noted DI usage and transaction-script style controllers.
- Abstractions: 3 abstract classes (`Student`, `AcademicStaff`, `FinancialAidPackage`); no interfaces. 38 concretes (33 entities + 4 controllers + `UniversityDbContext`).
- Grade: C for decoupling/SOLID (controllers tightly coupled to EF, no service/repo interfaces, limited polymorphism).
- Pattern density: 3 patterns / 41 classes ≈ 7.3%.

Next steps (if you want): 1) Introduce repository/service interfaces to decouple controllers from EF. 2) Add polymorphic behaviors or strategies for student/aid variants. 3) Extract transactional workflows into services to reduce controller responsibilities.
